DATA 602 - Certain Probability Models of Continuous Random Variables

© Jim Stallard 2019

Up to this point, you have been exposed various forms of discrete probability models that provide a probabilistic description of a certain type of event. For instance, the Binomial distribution describes the probabilistic behavior of a count observed after a series of \(n\) independent Bernoulli trials have been completed.

In this module, you will be exposed to certain types of continuous probability models.

The Uniform Distribution

Definition: A random variable \(X\) is said to follow a uniform distribution if and only if the probability density function of \(X\) is given by \[ f(x) = \left \{ \begin{array}{ll} \frac{1}{b - a} & {\rm for\:\:} a \leq x \leq b \\ 0 & {\rm otherwise} \\ \end{array} \right. \]

The cumulative distribution function of a Uniformly distributed random variable, \(P(X \leq X)\), is also given \[ F(x) = \left \{ \begin{array}{ll} 0 & {\rm for\:\;} x < a \\ \frac{x - a}{b - a} & {\rm for\:\:} a \leq x < b \\ 1 & {\rm for \:\:} x \geq b \\ \end{array} \right. \]

Below is an example of a uniformly distributed random variable \(X\) between 2 and 12:

In this instance, the area of rectangle should be equal to 1. This can be checked using the formula that finds the area of a rectangle, where the length is equal to \(12 - 2 = 10\) and the width is \(\frac{1}{12 - 2} = \frac{1}{10} = 0.10\) \[ Area = length*width = (12 - 2)*\frac{1}{12 - 2} = 1 \] This can be verified with either \[ \int_{2}^{12}\left(\frac{1}{12 - 2} \right)dx = \int_{2}^{12}\left(\frac{1}{10} \right)dx = \frac{1}{10}*(12 - 2) = 1 \]

Example 1: Consider the random variable \(X\) that is uniformly distributed between 2 and 12. Compute \(P(5 \leq X \leq 6)\)

Answer: Looking at the above distribution, to compute \(P(5 \leq X \leq 6)\) is to compute the area

\[ P(5 \leq X \leq 6) = \int_{5}^{6}\left(\frac{1}{12 - 2}\right)dx = ? \] Using our knowledge of probability and continuous random variables, this can be computed by

\[ \begin{aligned} P(5 \leq X \leq 6) = & \int_{5}^{6}\left(\frac{1}{12 - 2}\right)dx \\ = & \int_{5}^{6}\left(\frac{1}{10}\right)dx \\ = & \left(\frac{1}{10}\right)\int_{5}^{6}dx \\ = & \left(\frac{1}{10}\right)*(6 - 5) \\ = & 0.10 \end{aligned} \] This can also be computed using the cumulative distribution function of the Uniform distribuiton: \[ \begin{aligned} P(5 \leq X \leq 6) = & P(X \leq 6) - P(X \leq 5) \\ = & \overbrace{\left(\frac{6 - 2}{12 - 2}\right)}^{F(6)} - \overbrace{\left(\frac{6 - 2}{12 - 2}\right)}^{F(5)} \\ = & \left(\frac{4}{10} \right) - \left(\frac{3}{10} \right) \\ = & 0.10 \end{aligned} \]

This can also be computed with R. There are three built in functions that enable you to work with a Uniform distribution between two points:

  • dunif(x, a, b) will compute the *value of the probability density function \(\frac{1}{b - a}\) at the value of x
  • punif(x, a, b) will compute the cumulative probability at \(x\) or evaluates \(F(x) = P(X \leq x)\)
  • qunif(p, a, b) will return the \(pth\)-percentile for a given value of a Uniformly distributed random variable \(X\)

Since \[ P(5 \leq X \leq 6) = P(X \leq 6) - P(X \leq 5) = F(6) - F(5) \]

punif(6, 2, 12) - punif(5, 2, 12)  #computes P(X <= 6) - P(X <= 5)



Example 2: The cycling time for a truck hauling asphalt to a road paving construction site can be modeled by a Uniform distribution between 30 and 50 minutes. Compute the probability that the cycling time for a certain truck

(a) takes between 35 and 40 minutes.

Answer: Here the probability \(P(35 \leq X \leq 40)\) needs to be computed. Visually, the probability density function is provided below with the \(P(35 \leq X \leq 40)\) provided:

This probability is then computed as \[ \begin{aligned} P(35 \leq X \leq 40) = & \int_{35}^{40}\left(\frac{1}{50 - 30}\right)dx \\ = & \left(\frac{40 - 35}{50 - 30}\right) \\ = & \frac{5}{20} \\ = & 0.25 \end{aligned} \] or \[ \begin{aligned} P(35 \leq X \leq 40) = & P(X \leq 40) - P(X \leq 35) \\ = & F(40) - F(35) \\ = & \left(\frac{40 - 30}{50 - 30} \right) - \left(\frac{35 - 30}{50 - 30} \right) \\ = & \frac{5}{20} \\ = & 0.25 \end{aligned} \] R can be used to compute \(P(35 \leq X \leq 40)\). The command below uses the “cdf” approach:

punif(40, 30, 50) - punif(35, 30, 50)


(b) If the cycling time of a certain load of asphalt has taken at least 40 minutes, compute the probability that it will take at most 45 minutes.

Answer: In this instance, some event has occurred - the cycling time of the truck is at least 40 minutes \(X \geq 40\). Given this, it is requires to compute that the cycling time of this truck is at most/no more than 45 minutes, \(P(X \leq 45 | X \geq 40)\). \[ \begin{aligned} P(X \leq 45|X \geq 40) = & \frac{P((X \geq 40) \cap (X \leq 45))}{P(X \geq 40)} \\ = & \frac{P(40 \leq X \leq 45)}{P(X \geq 40)} \hspace{0.5in} ((X \geq 40) \cap (X \leq 45) = 40 \leq X \leq 45)\\ = & \frac{\int_{40}^{45}\left(\frac{1}{50 - 30} \right)dx}{\int_{40}^{50}\left(\frac{1}{50 - 30} \right)dx} \\ = & \frac{\frac{5}{20}}{\frac{10}{20}} \\ = & \frac{5}{10} \\ = & 0.50 \end{aligned} \] This is computed with the R code below

(punif(45, 30, 50) - punif(40, 30, 50))/(1 - punif(40, 30, 50))  #P(40 <= X < = 45)/(1 - P(X < = 40))

(c) Compute the 50th percentile. In other words, 50th of the time it will take a trunk hauling asphalt to the paving site at most how many minutes?

Answer: To compute the 50th percentile, or \(x_{50}\), we can use the cumulative probabilty distribution function of \(X\) and set it equal to 0.50: \[ \begin{aligned} 0.50 = & P(X \leq x_{50}) \\ 0.50 = & \left(\frac{x_{50} - 30}{50 - 30}\right) \\ 0.50 * (50 - 30) = & x_{50} - 30 \\ 10 + 30 = & x_{50} \\ 40 \:\:\text{minutes} = X_{50} \end{aligned} \] This can be computed with the qunif command below:

qunif(0.50, 30, 50)  #comptues the 50th percentile for a uniform distribution between 30 and 50
[1] 40

50% of the time it takes at most 40 minutes for a truck to pick up a load of asphalt, dump the load, and return to pick up another load. In other words, the median cycling time is 40 minutes.

The Mean/Expectd Value and Standard Deviation of a Uniform Distribution

Result: If \(X\) is a random variable that is uniformly distributed on the interval \([a,b]\), then \[ \mu_{X} = E(X) = \frac{a + b}{2} \hspace{1in} \sigma_{X} = \sqrt{\frac{(b - a)^{2}}{12}} \] Proof of Expected value: Althought you will not be required to demonstrate or rejurgitate proofs in this course, it might be worthwhile to demonstrate where the mean/expected value result came from: \[ \begin{aligned} E(X) = & \int_{all\:\:x}x*f(x)dx \\ = & \int_{a}^{b}x\left(\frac{1}{b - a} \right)dx \\ = & \left(\frac{1}{b - a} \right) \left[\frac{x^{2}}{2} \right]_{a}^{b} \\ = & \left(\frac{1}{b - a} \right) \left[\frac{b^{2}}{2} - \frac{a^{2}}{2}\right] \\ = & \left(\frac{1}{2(b - a)} \right)\left[b^{2} - a^{2} \right] \\ = & \left(\frac{1}{2(b - a)} \right)(b - a)(b + a) \hspace{0.5in}( b^{2} - a^{2} = (b - a)(b + a))\\ = & \frac{1}{2}(b + a) \end{aligned} \]

Refer to Example 2: How long can one expect it to take for a truck to deliver a laod of asphalt to the road paving site then return to pick up another load of asphalt? Also compute the standard deviation.

Answer: The expected/mean cycling time is computed as \[ \mu_{X} = E(X) = \frac{a + b}{2} = \frac{30 + 50}{2} = 40 \:\:\text{minutes} \] the standard deviation is \[ \sigma_{X} = SD(X) = \sqrt{\frac{(b - a)^{2}}{12}} = \sqrt{\frac{(50 - 30)^{2}}{12}} = 5.7777 \approx 5.78\:\:\text{minutes} \]

The Normal Distribution

The Normal distribution, sometimes referred to as the Gaussian distribution, is probably one of the most important probability distributions you will learn about. This distribution provides a basis for many of the statistical principles and procedures you will encounter in Data 602 and following Data courses. Below the Normal distibution is defined.

Definition: A random variable \(X\) is said to follow a normal distribution if and only if the probability distribution function of \(X\) is in the form \[ f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi * \sigma^{2}}}e^{- \frac{(x - \mu)^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}}} \hspace{0.5in} - \infty < x < + \infty, \:\: \sigma^{2} > 0 \] where \(\mu\) is the mean/expected value and \(\sigma\) is the standard deviation of the Normal distribution.

Below is the probability density function of a random variable modeled by the Normal distribution function with a mean \(\mu\) of 100 and a standard deviation of \(\sigma = 10\), or \[ f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi * 10^{2}}}e^{- \frac{(x - 100)^{2}}{2*10^{2}}} \hspace{0.5in} - \infty < x < + \infty, \:\: \sigma^{2} > 0 \]

Computing Probabilities Associated with a Normal Distribution Probability Model

The distribution given below models the behaviour of the amount of time it takes students at a certain university to register for their courses through the online registration system, with a mean of \(\mu = 12\) minutes and a standard deviaiton of \(\sigma = 3\) minutes:

Suppose we wanted to compute the probability that it takes a student between 8 and 15 minutes to register, or \(P(8 \leq X \leq 15\)). We would be finding the following area:

This probability is computed by \[ P(8 \leq X \leq 15) = \int_{8}^{15}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi * 3^{2}}}e^{- \frac{(x - 12)^{2}}{2 * 3^{2}}}dx = ? \] To compute such a probability we can create a function in R, the conduct the integration of said function between the two values of 8 and 15. However, R Studio has a build in “normal” function that saves us such an effort. YOu will not be asked to compute this integration in Data 602.

A shortcut to computing this probability invokes the R command pnorm(x,mean,sd), with the p in front provding R the instruction to compute the cumulative probability \(P(X \leq x)\) for a given mean \(\mu\) and a given standard deviation \(\sigma\).

To illustrate, suppose we were to compute the probability that it took a student at most 15 minutes to register for their courses, or \(P(X \leq 15)\). We side step the integration and compute this cumulative probability within R Studio.

pnorm(15,12,3) #computes P(X <= 15) for mu =12 and sigma = 3

and \[ P(X \leq 15) = \int_{-\infty}^{15}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi 3^{2}}}e^{- \frac{(x - 12)^{2}}{2 3^{2}}}dx = 0.841345 \] To compute the probabilty that it takes a student between 8 minutes and 15 minutes to register in R Studio, the difference between the two cumulative probabilities is computed in R Studio:

pnorm(15,12,3) - pnorm(8,12,3)  #P(X <= 15) - P(X <= 8)

and \[ P(8 \leq X \leq 15) = \int_{8}^{15}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \pi 3^{2}}}e^{- \frac{(x - 12)^{2}}{2 3^{2}}}dx = 0.750134 \]

Applications of the Normal Distribution Probability Model - Computing Percentiles

Illustration: The Society of Actuaries runs a series of professional examinations which much be passed by budding actuaries who wish to advance in their actuarial careers. One of these exams is Exam P - Probability. The exam scores for Exam P are Normally distributed with a mean of \(\mu_{X} = 70\%\) and a standard deviation of \(\sigma_{X} = 8\%\). In order to pass Exam P, a student must score above the 70th percentile. Compute the mark the student must earn in order to pass Exam P.

We can find the \(x\)-value such that \(P(X \leq x_{70})\) with the R command qnorm(percentile, mean, sd), where the percentile argument corresponds to the cumulative probability. In our case, we use

qnorm(0.70, 70, 8)   # returns a x-value such that P(X <= x) = 0.70

and \(x_{0} = 74.1952\). In order to pass Exam P, the student must acheive a mark above 74.1952% \(\approx\) 74.20%.

(b) between 50% and 65%.

Answer: Similar to part (a), the region below represents \(P(50 \leq X \leq 65)\):

(c) 90% of students who write Exam P score at most “how high”?

Answer: In this instance, you are not required to compute a probability. Rather, you have been given a probability. The 90th percentile statement means that \(0.90 = P(X \leq x_{90})\) from which the unknown value of \(x_{90}\) can be determined with the qnorm(percentile, mean, sd) command:

The Gamma Distribution

The two types of continuous distributions that have been covered thus far are both perfectly symmetrical. There is a different class of continuous probability distributions that

  1. only assume non-negative values (\(x \geq 0\))
  2. are right-skewed

One family of such distributions belongs to the Gamma family of distributions. The definition of a Gamma random variable is provided below.

Definition: A random variable \(X\) is said to follow a Gamma distribution if and only if the probability density function of \(X\) is given by \[ f(x) = \frac{1}{\Gamma(\alpha)\beta^{\alpha}}x^{\alpha - 1}e^{-\frac{x}{\beta}} \hspace{0.75in} \alpha, \beta > 0, \hspace{0.1in} x \geq 0 \] The Gamma distribution has two parameters, \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\); the mean/expected value and the standard deviation of the Gamma random variable are provided respectively,

\[ \mu_{X} = E(X) = \alpha*\beta \hspace{0.5in} \sigma_{X} = SD(X) = \sqrt{\alpha * \beta^{2}} \]

To give you a sense of “how” the Gamma distribution behaves for various values of \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\), below are three different types of Gamma distributions:

  • for \(\alpha = 2\) and \(\beta = 1\)
  • for \(\alpha = 2\) and \(\beta = 2\)
  • for \(\alpha = 2\) and \(\beta = 3\)

Obseve how as the value of the \(\beta\)-parameter increases from 1, then to 2, then to 3, the shape of the distribution becomes less right-skewed.

There are two special cases of Gamma distributions,

  1. When \(\alpha = 1\)
  2. When \(\beta = 2\) and \(\alpha = \frac{df}{2}\)

1. The Exponential Distribution

Definition: A random variable \(X\) is said to follow an Exponential distribution if and only if \(X\) follows a Gamma distribution with \(\alpha = 1\). The probability density function is then

\[ f(x) = \frac{1}{\Gamma(1)\beta^{1}}x^{1 - 1}e^{-\frac{x}{\beta}} = \frac{1}{\beta}e^{-\frac{x}{\beta}} \hspace{0.5in} {\rm for\:\:} x \geq 0 \] The mean/expected value and the standard deviation of an Exponentially distributed randomv variable is

\[ \mu_{X} = E(X) = \alpha * \beta = 1*\beta = \beta \hspace{1in} \sigma_{X} = \sqrt{1*\beta^{2}} = \beta \]

Below are various Exponential distributions with a a mean of (i) \(\beta = 1\) (ii) \(\beta = 2\) and (iii) \(\beta = 5\).

Illustration of the Exponential Distribution: The amount of time one spends waiting to be served by a cashier in a certain grocery store can be modeled by the Exponential distribution with a mean waiting time of 5 minutes. That is, \(X\) is Exponentially distributed with \(\mu_{X} = \beta = 5\) minutes. The distribution of \(X\) can be generated with the R code

Supose we wanted to compute the probability that a customer will wait at most 5 minutes until they are to be served by the cashier, \(P(X \leq 5)\). This computation can be accomplished in one of two ways: 1. \(P(X \leq 5)\) using the probability density function of the Exponential distribution where \(\beta = 5\) is \[ f(x) = \left(\frac{1}{5} \right)e^{-x/5} \:\: \text{for} \:\:x \geq 0 \] The area of interest in the graph above is

and \[ \begin{aligned} P(X \geq 50) = & \int_{0}^{5}\left(\frac{1}{5} \right)e^{-x/5}dx = \left[-e^{-x/5} \right]_{0}^{5} = 1 - e^{-1} = 1- 0.367879 = 0.6321206\approx 0.6321 \end{aligned} \] 2. Use of R. There are two built-in R commands specific for the Exponential distribution:

  • dexp(x, 1/beta) computes the value of the probability density function \(f(x)\) for a given value of \(\beta\)-parameter
  • pexp(x, 1/beta) computes \(P(X \leq x)\) for a given value of the \(\beta\)-parameter
  • qexp(p, 1/beta) computes the pth-percentiles for a given value of the \(\beta\)-parameter

In this instance, to compute \(P(0 \leq X \leq 5)\) the can use the pexp(x, 1/beta) is employed:

pexp(5,1/5) # P(X <= 5) with mean/beta = 5
[1] 0.6321206

and \[ P(X \leq 5) = \int_{0}^{5}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)e^{-x/5}dx = 0.6321206 \]

(c) Suppose you have waited to be served by the cashier for at least 5 minutes. Compute the probability that you will have to wait at most 10 minutes in total.

Answer: Here we need to compute \(P(X \leq 10| X \geq 5)\), which is computed with \[ \begin{align} P(X \leq 10 | X \geq 5) = & \frac{P(5 \leq X \leq 10)}{P(X \geq 5)} \\ = & \frac{\int_{5}^{10}\frac{1}{5}e^{-x/5}dx}{1- \int_{5}^{\infty}\frac{1}{5}e^{-x/5}dx} \\ = & \frac{{\rm pexp(10,1/5)} - {\rm pexp(5,1/5)}}{1- {\rm pexp(5,1/5)}} \end{align} \]

pexp(5, 1/5)
[1] 0.6321206

Result: Consider a random variable \(Y\) that counts the number of occurrences of a certain event in a well-defined time region with a mean \(\mu_{Y} = E(Y) = \lambda\). Another random variable \(X\) is defined to measure either of + the amount of that passes until the first event occurs + the amount of time that passes between successive events, \(Y_{i} - Y_{i - 1}\), called the interarrival time

\(X\) can be modeled by the Exponential distribution, where the mean is \(E(X) = \beta = \frac{1}{\lambda}\) and the probability density function of \(X\) is \[ f(x) = \frac{1}{\beta}e^{-x/\beta} = \lambda e^{-x\lambda} \hspace{0.5in} {\rm for\:\:} x \geq 0 \:\: {\rm and\:\:} \lambda > 0 \]

Example 2: \(X\) is a random variable that counts the number of visits to a certain website per second. From our understanding of how to model counts, this particular count can be modeled by the Poisson distribution1 with a mean of 100 visits per second, or \(\mu_{X} = E(X) = \lambda = 100\).


A random variable \(Y\) represents the amount of time that passes between successive visits to this website.

(a) Compute the mean/expected value of \(Y\), \(\mu_{Y}\) and the standard deviation of \(Y\), \(\sigma_{Y}\), both in seconds.

Answer: We expect 100 visits, on average, to occur in each second. So, we expect there to be an equal amount of time to pass between each of the 100 expected visits per second. Therefore, the mean of \(Y\) or \(E(Y)\) is computed with \[ E(Y) = \frac{1}{E(X)} = \frac{1}{\lambda} = \frac{1}{100} = 0.01 \:{\rm\;\:of\;\;a\:\:second} \]
  1. Create the distribution of \(Y\) in R Studio.

    Answer: The commands below create the Exponential distribution for \(Y\), the amount of time passing between successive visits with a probability density function \[ f(x) = \left(\frac{1}{0.01}\right)e^{-y/0.01} = 100e^{-100*y} \:\:\text{for}\:\; y \geq 0 \] 
x = seq(0,0.1,0.0025)

2. The Chi-Square (\(\chi^{2}\)) Distribution

The \(\chi^{2}\)-distribution has one parameter \(df\), which is often referrd to as the degrees of freedom, or \(df\). Below are three separate \(\chi^{2}\)-distributions, one with 1 degree of freedom, another with 4 degrees of freedom, and a third with 10 degrees of freedom:

The pchisq(x,df) returns \(P(\chi^{2}_{df} \leq x)\), the dchisq(x,df) returns the value of the \(\chi^{2}\) density function at \(x\), and qchisq(percentile, df) returns the \(x_{p}\) = pth-percentile of the \(\chi^{2}_{df}\).

Example 1: A random variable follows a \(\chi^{2}\) distribution with \(df = 8\).

  1. Compute \(P(5 \leq \chi^{2}_{8} \leq 15)\) with. R.

    Answer: To compute this probability the R-command pchisq(x, df) is used to compute the area below:

This probability is computed with the pchisq(x, df) command, which evaluates \(P(\chi^{2}_{df} \leq x)\).

pchisq(15,8) - pchisq(5,8)   # P(ChiSq_{15} <= 15) - P(chisq_{15} <= 8)
[1] 0.6984307

and \(P(5 \leq \chi^{2}_{8} \leq 15) = 0.69843\).

  1. Compute the 50th percentle \(x_{50}\) of a \(\chi^{2}_{8}\).

    Solution: Using R to find the value \(x_{50}\) such that \(P(\chi^{2}_{8} \leq x_{50}) = 0.50\):

The value of \(x_{50}\) is computed with the qchisq(percentile, df) command.

qchisq(0.50,8) #computes the 50th percentile of a Chi-square with df = 8 
[1] 7.344121

and \(x_{50} = 7.34412\). In this instance, 50% of the time a \(\chi^{2}\) random variable with \(df = 8\) is less than or equal to 7.34412.

Result: If a random variable follows a \(\chi^{2}\) distribution with \(df\), then the mean/expected value and standard deviation are \[ \mu_{X} = E(X) = \alpha * \beta = \frac{df}{2}*2 = df \hspace{0.5in} \sigma_{X} = SD(X) = \sqrt{2*df} \] Example 2: In Example 1, the mean and standard deviation of \(\chi^{2}_{8}\), or a \(\chi^{2}\) random variable with 8 degrees of freedom, is \[ \mu_{X} = E(X) = df = 8 \hspace{0.2in} \sigma_{X} = SD(X) = \sqrt{2*df} = \sqrt{2*8} = 4 \]
